<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>(((((((((((((((((((</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by TUC (CCS22)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The TUC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is the voice of Britain at work. Our overall objectives are to raise the quality of working life and promote </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">equality for all.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is TUC response has been drafted in consultation with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clean Coal Task Group (CCTG)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> joint energy industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">/TUC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">body formed to promote clean coal technologies within the UK. Its terms of reference are: “To identify an appropriate po</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">licy framework and supporting economic instruments and regulatory framework that would take forward the research, development and promotion and initiation of clean coal burn and carbon capture and storage technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The TUC welcomes t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he decision of the ECC Committee to undertake this timely Inquiry. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS deployment has reached a defining moment. Decisions taken in this period on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(1) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the scale and pace of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commercialisation programme and (2) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support measures </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through the Energy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Bill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Contracts for Difference </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will determine whether or not the UK will develop a national CCS industry.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An ambitious CCS programme is essential to decarbonise the UK’s power and industrial sectors. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">potential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">employment, skills and economic benefits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of such a programme are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">considerable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, providing a vital route to rebalance the economy between high and low carbon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">between industry and finance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as well as to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provide a secure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">long term future for the UK’s indigenous coal mining industry. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">period, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he main barriers to developing CCS appear to be around the formation and implementation of government energy policy. The two key strands of government support for are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Electricity Market Reforms (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">EMR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the CCS commercialisation programme. These </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">two p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rocesses must work in parallel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">maximise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> momentum and technological advance. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A major potential benefit from CCS deployment will be to secure the long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">term future for UK coal mining. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without investment in CCS there is no long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">term future for the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coal industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and its 9,000 employees.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">But actions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> taken now to invest in CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and reform our electricity market can secure this core industry in a low carbon economy for the long term.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK-based coal power in the energy mix </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enhances security of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">supply and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">helps to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">insulates us against the volatility of fossil fuel prices. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government should therefore develop a roadmap for UK coal mining alongside its EMR implementation plan, to provide security for UK coal investors and its workforce.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CS is t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">echnology is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">essential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to help decarbonise UK manufacturing processes in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">energy in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tensive industries such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">steel, cement and certain chemical</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst we welcome DECC’s heat strategy, the TUC is concerned at the pace and scale of government support for i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ndustrial CCS. Rather than industrial and power CCS technologies developing in parallel, they appear to be moving forward in sequence. For example, there is no industrial mechanism in the Energy Bill to incentivise industrial CCS.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">RESPONSE TO QUESTIONS</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Wha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">t types of CCS technology are currently being developed and how do they differ from one another? </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS technologies are being developed for both the power and industrial sectors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> most cost effective route map for CCS lies in the deployment of regional CCS capture networks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for power and industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the UK’s industrial heartlands, such as the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Aire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Valley, and in cluster</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> initiatives such as the North E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ast Process Industri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es (NEPIC) p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roject</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> focussed on petrochemical</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The power sector leads CCS technology development, principally through well understood and developed processes – pre-and post-combustion and oxy-fuel technologies. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The current CCS commercialisation programme is focussed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on two options: at Peterhead, Scotland, a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">full-scale gas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">project</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, potentially capturing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a million </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tonnes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of CO2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> annually; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">426MWe White Rose demonstration project at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Drax</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Oxyfuel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has been developed in Europe by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Alstom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Doosan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Babcock and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can be applied to both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ew and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">retrofit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ted installations.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are other full scale projects, such as 2Co Energy’s Don Valley project, in South Yorkshire, proceeding in parallel with the commercialisation programme that intend to ap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ply for a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Final Investment Decision (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> enabling </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Contract for Difference (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the power sector, one of the three main ways in which greenhouse gas emissions from industrial heat demand can be reduced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">energy efficiency, fuel switching, and indust</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rial CCS. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As the DECC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Heat Strategy</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> acknowledges, industrial CCS could be a key technology for the decarbonisation of industry sector, potentially allowing energy intensive industries to continue using fossil fuels while significantly reducing emissions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Much </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">long-term industrial abatement potential lies in CCS technology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ndustries which emit carbon from manufacturing process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iron and steel, cement, oil refining and chemicals.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The TUC concurs with this view of the importance of industrial CCS. In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an increasingly carbon constrained world, considerable first mover advantages are available from the early development of industry CCS. As DECC points out, industrial facilities which are located close to other industries or power stations and storage site</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s are more likely to be able to implement CCS if they can share transport and storage infrastructure.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Industrial sectors need to develop and trial a range of capture technologies, for example:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in iron and steel, through a top gas recycling blast furnace co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">upled with CCS; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in cement manufacture through post-combustion capture technology using amines; and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in chemicals where a number of processes are good contenders for post-reaction capture due to large volume, highly concentrated CO2 streams.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst we welc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ome the heat strategy, the TUC is concerned at the pace and scale of government support for industrial CCS. Rather than industrial and power CCS technologies developing in parallel, they appear to be moving forward in sequence. For example, there is no ind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustrial mechanism in the Energy Bill to incentivise industrial CCS.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">What contribution could CCS make towards the UK’s decarbonisation targets? Are the UK Government’s expectations reasonable in this regard?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CCS contribution: a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">dvice from the Committee on Cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">imate Change</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he Committee on Climate Change </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(CCC) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimates</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the UK’s decarbonising power sector will require </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approximately 18-20GW of CCS for coal and gas by 2030.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government’s independent advice from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provides an energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scenario </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to reach the UK’s 2030 energy decarbonisation target. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">power sector currently accounts for around 25% of UK greenhouse gas emissions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An indicative generation mix to achieve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a carbon intensity of 50-100g/KWh by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2030 is 40% nuclear, 40% renewable, 15% CC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S, and around 5% unabated gas-fired generation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">power generation capacity of about 12</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GW by 2030, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">equate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to 18</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-20</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GW of CCS for coal and ga</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Given the long lead times for major infrastructure projects such as these, and the fact none has yet ma</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">de its final investment decision, the UK needs to move swiftly if it is to have a realistic chance of achieving this target.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCC’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ower sector scenario for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ourth </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arbon </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">udget was designed to develop a portfolio of low-carbon technology options, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and includes cost-effective investment in mature low-carbon technologies together with investment in less mature technologies required to support learning and innovation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The CC conclude that:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> “The current proposal to support four CCS power generation proj</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ects (in the Coalition Agreement, reconfirmed in the 2010 Spending Review), would result in a critical mass for potential roll-out from the early 2020s. It is important that a funding mechanism for the four projects is finalised and that these are tendered</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in 2011 to facilitate early deployment</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The CCC estimates that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the power sector will capture a larger amount of CO2 per year than industry up until 2040, from when power and industry are projected to capture similar quantities annually</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They state that:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“There is a growing role for CCS in industry through the 2020s, which by 2030 reduces emissions by around 5 MtCO2....</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To ensure that this technology is available for deployment from the 2020s, a policy approach is required which either funds demonstration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, or ensures that demonstration elsewhere (e.g. under the EU’s CCS demonstration programme) will provide scope for timely deployment in the UK.”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CO2 Sense – regional CCS infrastructure</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">From a regional perspective, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a study by CO2 Sense of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The national, regi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">onal and local economic benefits of the Yorkshire and Humber carbon capture and storage cluster</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> shows that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the successful development of a regional CCS infrastructure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Aire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Valley</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">could capture </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approximately 60</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">million tonnes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of carbon emissions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r year </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from power and industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sources. The initial ‘core’ cluster </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">act as a catalyst for the establishment of a wider cluster. The core cluster consists of three elements:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ight-sized CO2 pipeline and saline storage provided by National Grid; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ite Rose Project, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Drax</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Selby, supported through the CCS commercialisation programme; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Don Valley Power Project, a new coal fired power plant under development by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2Co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Energy, associated with the Hatfield coal mine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">near Doncaster, that is proceeding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in parallel with the CCS commercialisation programme competition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2Co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">project was not shortlisted under the commercialisation programme, even though </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rank</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">first</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in Europe under the NER300 programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">among the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">top ten global CCS project</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Bloomberg New Energy Finance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. To incentivise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS investments outside the scope of the commercialisation programme, the government will need to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the enabling Contract for Difference for CCS includes appropriate risk sharing for early projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It will also need to provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sufficient capacity in the Levy Control Framework to 2020 for CCS capital investment.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he UK Government’s expectations</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Coalition agreement said: “We will continue public sector investment in carbon capture and storage (CC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S) technology for four coal-fired power stations.” But current ambitions for the CCS commercialisation programme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reduce to “up to two projects” receiving final approval</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, according to DECC comments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and possibly only a single project</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">CCS R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">oadmap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(2012) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">does not provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">targets for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deployment. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Instead, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it provides the plain statements of fact that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">potential CCS storage capacity of the North Sea basin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is huge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS technology is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">currently the only means by which fossil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fuels can be maintained within the UK generation mix, whilst meeting our 2050 carbon targets.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">From the TUC’s perspective CCS is at a critical stage. The Coalition’s initial ambition of four CCS demonstration projects would appear to meet the minimum requ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">irement recommended by the CCC. The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> TUC therefore believe the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> government needs to immediately return to its initial ambition for four CCS demonstration projects, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure these can be incentivised quickly through the Final Investment Decision enabling Co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntracts for Difference (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) that should be available from the end of 2013. It needs to ensure that measures in the Energy Bill incentivise further power sector CCS projects under the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> process.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Are there any potential benefits (e.g. the ability to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">export CCS technology abroad) of successfully developing CCS to the UK economy and, if so, what are they?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Yes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DECC acknowledges that C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CS represents a major green growth opportunity for the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> stating that “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If CCS opportunities develop as anticipated, bene</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fits for UK-based firms have been estimated to be between £3 - 6.5 billion a year by the late 2020s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.”</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[viii]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, the government has not developed a comprehensive analysis of the economic, fiscal and social benefits of CCS. The TUC believes that such researc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h would strengthen the case for CCS deployment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DECC envisages </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS Commercialisation Programme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(launched in April 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as supporting “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a strong and robust supply chain in the UK, creating jobs and markets locally and nationally to serve the early CCS p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lant and later clusters of CCS activity. Playing to the UK’s business strengths and favouring projects clustering in regions reflects the Government’s ambition to capture opportunities for ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">green </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">jobs’ that will arise from an emerging market for CCS, and r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecognises the concerns of UK industry about the development of CCS infrastructure.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[ix]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the UK, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CO2 Sense </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">study (see above) revealed that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he Yorkshire and Humber</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> CCS cluster </span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[x]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the potential to generate, both directly and indirectly, an economic i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mpact totalling some £1.255 billion up to 2030</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Economic benefits are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">greatest during the overlap between construction and operation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in 2017 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">least 6,000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> net additional FTE jobs and £245m net</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">additional GVA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are realised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Its long-term </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">economic impact by 2050 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">could exceed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> £26 billion - sustaining and creating thousands of jobs across Yorkshire and the Humber.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Aire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Valley CCS cluster: peak employment, full time equivalent posts</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:92.4pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Project</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:92.4pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Construction</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; b