ticularly important as many of these sectors cannot afford the full cost of fitting CCS.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A roadmap for coal</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A major potential benefit from CCS deployment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will be to secure the long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">term future for UK coal mining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and its 9,000 employees.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without investment in CCS there is no long term future for the UK coal industry. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Actions taken now to invest in CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and reform our electricity market can secure this core industry in a low carbon economy for the long term. Delays will drive investment and dependency on gas fired power without resolving the challenge of CO2 capture, whilst losing a once-only opportunity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for global leadership in the vital CCS industry. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK mines </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in 2012 mined </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">over 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> million tonnes of coal a year, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coal power stations generate over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">38%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the UK’s electricity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">compared with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">28</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">% from gas generators. At peak times, we turn to the e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">xceptional flexibility of coal power for up to 50% of our electricity supply. Coal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">directly provides over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,000 jobs in deep and surface mines and ancillary functions, whilst coal power stations employ over 4,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> staff, many in skilled quality em</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ployment. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government should therefore develop a roadmap for UK coal mining alongside its EMR implementation plan, to provide security for UK coal investors and its workforce.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main barriers (e.g. economic, political, regulatory, scientific</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> and social) to developing large-scale integrated CCS projects in the UK and internationally? How can they be overcome? </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">main barrier to developing CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in this period </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">appear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s to be the slow </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">formation and implementation of government energy policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to su</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pport CCS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">two key strands of government support for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are EMR reforms and the CCS commercialisation programme. These two processes must work in parallel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to ensure the maximum momentum and technological advance. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">overnment’s Electricity Market Reform (E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">MR)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The EMR includes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">measures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to support all low-carbon generation with Contracts for Differences (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfDs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">providing for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deployment of CCS in the power sector. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Key tests for the EMR if it is to drive CCS investment include: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a transparent and long-term </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commitment through a CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> strike price setting and allocation process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">long-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">term </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">confidence to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS developers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">contract strike price over the right time frame to facilitate investment.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The EMR has so far failed to provide clarity in any of these t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hree areas. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The draft </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">EMR </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Delivery Plan</span><a name="_ednref11"></a><a href="#_edn11">[xi]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(July 2013) is unhelpful in its range of zero to 12GW of CCS by 2030, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">even </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the upper limit almost half of the ambition set out by the Committee on Climate Change, of 18-20GW by 2030.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The delivery plan says: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sed on central demand and decarbonisation assumptions (100g CO2/KWh) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">[the scenario] </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">illustrates a generation mix that would be consistent with CCS costs and deployment circumstances being favourable compared to other technologies. In this scenario, three C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CS plants are built by the end of 2020, with commercial deployment of both gas and coal CCS throughout the 2020s- leading to deployment of around 12 GW CCS in 2030.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CCS commercialisation programme</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The latest CCS Commercialisation Programme is tasked with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">launching a process to ensure the general deployment of CCS for coal and gas by the 2020s. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">From an early commitment to four CCS projects, currently there may be support for only one or two. As a bare minimum, the government should rapidly conclude negotiat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ions at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Drax</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Peterhead, with a view to plant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> being operational</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by 2018 at the latest. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">More than that, the government should retain its commitment to four demonstration projects and consider returning to other projects under development, offering them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clear and speedy alternatives either through the CCS competition or via </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfDs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Sustained deployment is critical at this stage.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Is the UK Government’s approach, set out in its CCS Roadmap, likely to incentivise development of CCS in the UK?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach lacks the necessary pace and scale. As noted above, currently the main drivers of CCS are reliant on effective government policy. The two key strands of government support for CCS are the EMR reforms and the CCS commercialisation programme. These </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">two processes must work in parallel, not sequentially, to ensure the maximum momentum, technological advance and robustness of the programme against possible future project cancellations.  At present there is a strong perception that the government is resi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sting further CCS deployment until the commercialisation projects are underway.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Could the successful development of CCS improve international efforts to mitigate climate change? What role could UK CCS play in this? </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Yes. CCS is acknowledged to be a crucial transitional technology for climate change mitigation. The UK has a crucial seedbed role to play, although there is a now a clear danger that other countries will move ahead more rapidly, so that the UK loses techno</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">logical and market leadership. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Canada, the Boundary Dam</span><a name="_ednref12"></a><a href="#_edn12">[xii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> CCS project has been completed, a 110 MW coal pow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r plant with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">retrofit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCS technology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> due to start operating in 2014. The total cost of the project is estimated to be $1.24 billion, with $240 mi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">llion from the federal government in 2011, of which about $180 million has already been spent. The provincial government is also supporting the project. Employment includes 20 at the R&amp;D stage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, peak</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> construction employment of 1,500 and 41 operational emplo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">yees. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/190149/16_04-DECC-The_Future_of_Heating_Accessible-10.pdf</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Committee on Climate Change, advice to the Energy Secretary, 13 September 2012.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Committee on Climate Change, advice to the Energy Secretary, 13 September 2012.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn4"></a><a href="#_ednref4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Committee on Climate Change, Fourth Carbon Budget, December 2010.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn5"></a><a href="#_ednref5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.co2sense.co.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">uk/files/2113/5031/6058/CCS_CO2Sense_Exec_summary_FINAL.pdf</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn6"></a><a href="#_ednref6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.co2sense.co.uk/files/2113/5031/6058/CCS_CO2Sense_Exec_summary_FINAL.pdf</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn7"></a><a href="#_ednref7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.utilityweek.co.uk/news/news_story.asp?id=198331&amp;title=Final+two+CCS+projects+named</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn8"></a><a href="#_ednref8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> AEA,  2010, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">uture Value of Carbon Abatement Technologies in Coal and Gas Power Generation to UK Industry. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.decc.gov.uk/assets/decc/What%20we%20do/UK%20energy%20supply/Energy%20mix/Carbon%20capture%20and%20storage/1_20100629105946_e_@@_futurevalueCATUKindustr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">y.pdf.  </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_edn9"></a><a href="#_ednref9">[ix]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">CCS Roadmap:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:1